sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Recon Command Output Piped To Findstr.EXE
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects the execution of a potential recon command where the results are piped to "findstr". This is meant to trigger on inline calls of "cmd.exe" via the "/c" or "/k" for example.
Attackers often time use this technique to extract specific information they require in their reconnaissance phase.

match_context.values: @{Product=Microsoft Windows Operating System; CurrentDirectory=C:\Program Files (x86)\AutoIt3\; OriginalFileName=Cmd.Exe; Hashes=MD5=F3BDBE3BB6F734E357235F4D5898582D,SHA256=3685495D051137B1C4EFDE22C26DF0883614B6453B762FA84588DA55ED2E7744,IMPHASH=0AF8419BE362159398343D7B31721726; Description=Windows Command Processor; EventID=1; ParentCommandLine="C:\Program Files (x86)\AutoIt3\AutoIt3.exe" "C:\Users\george\Desktop\script.0.au3"; CommandLine=C:\Windows\system32\cmd.exe /c tasklist /svc | find "svchost.exe" >> \\192.168.2.1\joe-office-g8-19\logs\services.log; FileVersion=10.0.17134.1 (WinBuild.160101.0800); ParentImage=C:\Program Files (x86)\AutoIt3\AutoIt3.exe; IntegrityLevel=High; Image=C:\Windows\SysWOW64\cmd.exe; Company=Microsoft Corporation}

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.
